<div class="iDevice_wrapper FreeTextIdevice" id="id262">
<div class="iDevice emphasis0">
<div id="ta262_85" class="block iDevice_content">
<div class="dentro_contenidos" style="display: block;" id="pagina_1">
<ul>
<li>In is used for something inside a limited area while on is used for a point on a surface, with floor and ceiling, and for public transport vehicles.</li>
<li>At is used for places in terms of their function or as a meeting place.</li>
<li>Over is used for movement to the other side of something high and across to express movement to the other side of a flat area.</li>
<li>Above and over are used when something is higher than something else</li>
<li>Under and below are used when something is lower than something else.</li>
<li>Along is used for something which follows a line and through means from one side of something to the other side of it.</li>
<li>By and beside are used in the same way meaning “next to”.</li>
<li>Between is used when we speak about two things while among is used when we speak about a group.</li>
<li>We use behind to mean that you are facing the back of that thing or person and beyond is used to express that something is further away from us than something else.</li>
<li>We use as to say something or someone is that thing, before a subject followed by a verb, to mean because, after certain verbs including describe, consider and regard, to make comparisons, to mean for example and with same…as.</li>
<li>We use like to mean similar to (especially with the verbs look, sound, smell, seem, taste, etc) and to mean for example.</li>
<li>We use zero conditional for things which are generally true and scientific facts.</li>
<li>We use first conditional to express a future condition the speaker considers possible. Or likely.</li>
<li>The second conditional is used to express a present or future condition which is imaginary, contrary to the facts, impossible or improbable.</li>
<li>Third conditional is used to express something which did not happen in the past and its results which are imaginary.</li>
</ul>
